== Etymology ==
BmK is the abbreviation for ''Buthus martensi'' Karsch, an old name for the scorpion that is the source of BmKAEP; AEP is an abbreviation for anti-epilepsy peptide.  At the [[National Center for Biotechnology Information|NCBI]] Protein Database, the full name of this peptide is listed as "Toxin BmKAEP".<ref name="NCBI-Protein37999913">{{cite web
|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/37999913
|title=Toxin BmKAEP
|publisher=[[National Center for Biotechnology Information|NCBI]] [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein Protein database]
|accessdate=25 October 2010}}</ref>

== Source ==
[[File:Snímek 283.jpg|thumb|right|Manchurian scorpion ''(Mesobuthus martensii)'']]
BmKAEP is one of the components of ''Mesobuthus martensii''′s venom,<ref name="first article">{{cite journal |last1=Goudet |first1=C |last2=Chi |first2=CW |last3=Tytgat |first3=J |title=An overview of toxins and genes from the venom of the Asian scorpion Buthus martensi Karsch |journal=Toxicon |volume=40 |issue=9 |pages=1239–58 |year=2002 |pmid=12220709 |doi=10.1016/S0041-0101(02)00142-3}}</ref> a well-known scorpion belonging to the [[Buthidae]] family, which is found distributed throughout Eastern Asia and China.

== Chemistry ==
BmKAEP is an inhibitory [[β-toxin]] and thus, a Na<sup>+</sup> channel inhibitor. As with other mammal and insect toxins, BmKAEP is classified according to species and mechanism of action.<ref name="third article">{{cite journal |last1=Wang |first1=Chun-Guang |last2=He |first2=Xiao-Lin |last3=Shao |first3=Feng |last4=Liu |first4=Wei |last5=Ling |first5=Min-Hua |last6=Wang |first6=Da-Cheng |last7=Chi |first7=Cheng-Wu |title=Molecular characterization of an anti-epilepsy peptide from the scorpion Buthus martensi Karsch |journal=European Journal of Biochemistry |volume=268 |issue=8 |pages=2480–5 |year=2001 |pmid=11298767 |doi=10.1046/j.1432-1327.2001.02132.x}}</ref> 

BmKAEP is a 61-amino-acid protein derived from an 85-amino-acid precursor. The mature protein contains 8 cysteine residues that establish 4 [[disulfide bridges]] (4C-C).<ref name="third article"/> Despite its high homology with other depressant toxins, BmKAEP differs from them at residues 6, 7 and 39, which is thought to be important in determining its unique function.<ref name="third article"/> Its lysine residue, at position 51, also has a special feature: it interacts with mammalian Na<sup>+</sup> channels.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yuan |first1=Yuzhe |last2=Luo |first2=Lan |last3=Peigneur |first3=Steve |last4=Tytgat |first4=Jan |last5=Zhu |first5=Shunyi |title=Two recombinant depressant scorpion neurotoxins differentially affecting mammalian sodium channels |journal=Toxicon |volume=55 |issue=8 |pages=1425–33 |year=2010 |pmid=20219516 |doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2010.02.019}}</ref>

